explanation:
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit: directly called by OS_ForEachObjectOfType; its implementation must be inspected because it may invoke callbacks or other routines that perform string comparisons (transitively reachable from the target).
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry: directly called inside the iterator loop; must be analyzed because it may perform comparisons (including string comparisons) on iterator data or call functions that do.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: directly called at the end of the iterator; its implementation may perform cleanup that uses string comparisons.
- OS_ForEachFilterCreator: passed as the filter callback to OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit; this function may be invoked by the iterator and could use memcmp to compare null-terminated strings — must be checked.
- OS_ForEachDoCallback: passed to OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry and executed for each entry; it may perform string comparisons using memcmp and so must be inspected.
- OS_GetMaxForObjectType: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit (from the static call graph); include to cover transitive uses of string comparison inside iterator initialization.
- OS_GetBaseForObjectType: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit; include for the same transitive-reachability reason.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit; transaction init/lookup code may compare strings (names/ids) and must be checked.
- OS_Unlock_Global: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry; include because locking/unlocking wrappers sometimes call helper routines that compare identifiers/names.
- OS_ObjectIdFromToken: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry; likely to translate tokens to objects/names and could use string comparison — must be inspected.
- OS_Lock_Global: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry; include for completeness of the mutual-exclusion wrapper analysis.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy; include to cover any cleanup code that might compare strings.
- memcmp: the Standard Library function referenced by the MISRA rule; include so the analyzer can locate all uses of memcmp in the above symbols and determine whether any use is comparing null-terminated strings.

Note: The list focuses on direct callees of the target and the callbacks passed into the iterator (and their immediate callees from the provided static graph). These symbols are sufficient to find any transitive uses of memcmp that would cause the target function to violate the MISRA rule (i.e., if any reachable function compares null-terminated strings with memcmp). UT_ExecuteBasicHandler and UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData appear in the static graph but are test harness stubs; include them only if the build under analysis uses those stubs in the path — otherwise they are not required for analyzing the real implementation of OS_ForEachObjectOfType.
